---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const title = 'Running AI locally, for beginners';
const description =
  'A plain-language first step for understanding local AI inference before reading the full technical guide.';

const firstRunSteps = [
  {
    title: 'Start with one small model',
    body: 'Pick a small text model before trying anything large. A useful first target is a 3B to 7B model with 4-bit quantization.'
  },
  {
    title: 'Use one runtime',
    body: 'A runtime is the program that loads the model and makes it answer. The full AI Lab article uses llama.cpp as the first concrete path.'
  },
  {
    title: 'Ask one safe test question',
    body: 'Use public or non-sensitive text first. Confirm the model responds before giving it anything personal or important.'
  },
  {
    title: 'Notice the trade-off',
    body: 'Local AI can improve privacy and learning, but it is limited by your computer. Bigger models need more memory, storage, and patience.'
  }
];

const safetyChecks = [
  'Do not paste secrets, passwords, private account data, or sensitive internal context.',
  'Check whether the answer is useful before trusting it.',
  'If the model is too slow or fails to load, use a smaller model.',
  'Treat local inference as a learning lab first, not a production system.'
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <section class="card signal-hero" aria-labelledby="beginner-topic-title">
    <div class="signal-overlay" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="signal-grid" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="hero-content">
      <p class="hero-badge">Beginner article</p>
      <h1 id="beginner-topic-title">Running AI locally</h1>
      <p>
        Running AI locally means using an AI model on your own computer instead
        of sending every prompt to a cloud service. For beginners, the first
        goal is not to master the whole stack. It is to understand what is
        happening and complete one safe first run.
      </p>
      <div class="cta" aria-label="Beginner local inference actions">
        <a class="primary" href="/topics/running-inference-locally/">
          Go deeper into the technical guide
        </a>
        <a href="/beginners/module-0/">Back to Module 0 path</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card featured" aria-labelledby="plain-meaning">
    <div class="section-title">
      <div>
        <p class="pill inline">Plain meaning</p>
        <h2 id="plain-meaning">What this means</h2>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>
      A model is the file that contains learned patterns. Inference is the act
      of using that model to produce an answer. Local inference means the model
      runs on your device, through a runtime, and produces text without needing
      a hosted chat app for that specific run.
    </p>
    <p>
      You are not training a model. You are using an already-trained model in a
      more controlled environment.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card" aria-labelledby="why-local">
    <div class="section-title">
      <div>
        <p class="pill inline">Why it matters</p>
        <h2 id="why-local">Why a beginner should care</h2>
      </div>
    </div>
    <ul class="subtopic-list">
      <li class="subtopic-bullet">
        <span class="bullet-dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        <div>
          <div class="subtopic-title">Control</div>
          <p>
            You can learn how models run without depending on one hosted
            product.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="subtopic-bullet">
        <span class="bullet-dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        <div>
          <div class="subtopic-title">Privacy habit</div>
          <p>
            Local does not make every use safe, but it teaches you to think
            about where data goes.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="subtopic-bullet">
        <span class="bullet-dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        <div>
          <div class="subtopic-title">Better judgment</div>
          <p>
            You see the limits directly: speed, memory, model size, quality, and
            setup friction.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card" aria-labelledby="first-path">
    <div class="section-title">
      <div>
        <p class="pill inline">First path</p>
        <h2 id="first-path">The smallest useful path</h2>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="stacked">
      {
        firstRunSteps.map((step, index) => (
          <article class="info-panel path-step">
            <strong>
              {index + 1}. {step.title}
            </strong>
            <p>{step.body}</p>
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card" aria-labelledby="safe-first-prompt">
    <div class="section-title">
      <div>
        <p class="pill inline">Try safely</p>
        <h2 id="safe-first-prompt">A safe first prompt</h2>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>Use something public or invented first:</p>
    <pre><code>I am learning how local AI works.
Explain the difference between running a model locally and using a hosted chat app.
Use simple language, one analogy, and three beginner safety tips.</code></pre>
  </section>

  <section class="card" aria-labelledby="safety-checks">
    <div class="section-title">
      <div>
        <p class="pill inline">Guardrails</p>
        <h2 id="safety-checks">What to check before going further</h2>
      </div>
    </div>
    <ul>
      {safetyChecks.map((check) => <li>{check}</li>)}
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card" aria-labelledby="go-deeper">
    <div class="section-title">
      <div>
        <p class="pill inline">Go deeper</p>
        <h2 id="go-deeper">When you want the real setup</h2>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>
      The beginner version gives you the map. The full technical article walks
      through the local runtime path, model size choices, quantization, and a
      concrete llama.cpp example.
    </p>
    <div class="cta" aria-label="Go deeper links">
      <a class="primary" href="/topics/running-inference-locally/">
        Read the full technical article
      </a>
      <a href="/beginners/module-0/">Back to Module 0 path</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
